WEBVTT

00:05.903 --> 00:12.150
This is an interview with Mike Arisco by Stephen 
Huggs in Houston, Texas, 11-5-88. I need

00:12.671 --> 00:25.125
your name, place of birth, location and date for 
Vietnam. Okay, my name is Mike Arisco. I was, at

00:28.449 --> 00:35.877
that time, I was living in Port Opera, graduating 
from Thomas Jefferson in Port Opera. I was in the

00:36.599 --> 00:44.846
United States Marine Corps in 1966 through 69, but 
entered Vietnam in 67 through 69. All right. And

00:46.728 --> 00:48.249
what service organization were you in? Marine 
Corps. In the Marine Corps. And what was your job

00:49.550 --> 00:50.751
specialty? I was 2533 was what my specialty was, 
which is communications. But a lot of times you get

00:56.036 --> 01:00.680
stuck in some of the weirdest jobs while you were 
there. I was with H&S, 3rd Engineers is what I was

01:01.561 --> 01:06.505
working with. Originally, I started out as 
sweeping highways in the morning for landmines.

01:15.102 --> 01:19.328
That's what my original job was, beginning at 
communications. Later took over communications

01:19.348 --> 01:23.334
of the area and then started working. We did toward 
the end of my first tour, then through my next tour

01:23.394 --> 01:31.586
was patrol, working with H&S. Were you 
communication on patrol? No. No, I wasn't. Okay.

01:36.539 --> 01:41.824
When I say no, I wasn't communications. When I 
became a sergeant, I was still part of

01:43.326 --> 01:52.114
communications, but I enjoyed going out more than 
sitting in the Cointree area. I just didn't like

01:52.154 --> 01:53.255
sitting there. I liked taking off. Now, when you 
say communications, just about everybody in our

01:56.338 --> 02:02.044
squad could work the communications. We all took 
turns with it, if that's what you mean. We had a

02:05.227 --> 02:06.428
radio operator. Okay. Okay. All right. And why in 
particular did you choose to fight and be not?

02:12.490 --> 02:13.632
Because I was scared to go to jail. At that time, no 
one wants to go to jail. No one wants to die. But I

02:21.783 --> 02:25.828
felt I was scared, as everybody else was. But I was 
afraid that if I didn't go, I'm going to jail. And I

02:29.893 --> 02:32.397
was more afraid of that. I was more afraid of what 
would happen to me if I didn't go than if I did go.

02:36.402 --> 02:36.482
Hmm. And why did you choose the Marine Corps? 
Because I'm stupid. No, I picked the Marine Corps

02:41.569 --> 02:50.339
because of my personality and the way that I am. I am 
a person who likes to do spontaneous things. When I

02:53.343 --> 03:00.312
entered the Marine Corps, I was fooling, of 
course, with the lower Neanderthal people. Some

03:00.352 --> 03:02.334
of the dumbest things they made us do. But I could 
get away with more. if i if i did not show up for three

03:07.478 --> 03:36.372
days to an area let's say when i when i was in uh when i 
was in the uh san diego let's say when i was

03:07.478 --> 03:36.372
stationed there for a while which was near 
oceanside or wherever i was stationed i'd go meet

03:07.478 --> 03:36.372
some girl be gone for three days and just say i lost 
my way back or i had car trouble and they'll believe

03:07.478 --> 03:36.372
me it was it was unique how ignorance confess your 
own ignorance and but again i also looked at it when

03:36.925 --> 04:05.903
i was in the marine corps we had a tradition we 
didn't leave anybody behind if someone was shot we

03:36.925 --> 04:05.903
didn't leave them we took them back body and all 
sometimes so uh again that's dumb reasons i guess

03:36.925 --> 04:05.903
but that was my reason all right did you receive any 
uh instruction about the country or the nature of

03:36.925 --> 04:05.903
the conflict no that was when i received the 
information Okay, let's start over here. When I

04:08.617 --> 04:14.527
entered the Marine Corps, I spent boot camp, and 
then I went to weapons training. We went to Camp

04:15.549 --> 04:19.776
Pendleton for about six weeks to learn how to use 
certain weapons. There we had maybe a few days of

04:20.498 --> 04:28.111
talking about Vietnam because that's what 
everybody was talking about, but nothing on

04:20.498 --> 04:28.111
Vietnam. It wasn't until I really got into country 
And that, I think, was our major problem. I don't

04:33.210 --> 04:37.234
know if other units did have any indoctrination of 
the country. We didn't. And I think one of our

04:38.235 --> 04:40.797
problems, we never understood the people. And not 
understanding them, we insulted them more than we

04:41.758 --> 04:48.325
ever, by helping them, we insulted them more. One 
example, when you go into a village, when kids run

04:48.806 --> 04:58.035
up to you, you always just say, hey, here's some 
candy. And you're trying to be nice to them when you

04:58.075 --> 05:01.118
know it's a friendly village. At that point, when 
we first walked into a village, we did not know that

05:01.705 --> 05:16.624
before I even stepped into the village, I've 
already insulted everyone in that village four

05:01.705 --> 05:16.624
and five times and never even knew it because I was 
never told of their customs. And I guess you could

05:16.925 --> 05:20.589
say it's the Marine Corps' fault because we're out 
there fighting a war. But again, we lost the

05:20.970 --> 05:22.933
villagers. We never had them on our side. Of 
course, they were more afraid of the enemy. than

05:26.984 --> 05:28.706
they were of us. But like when you enter a village, 
the first person you're supposed to talk to is the

05:28.806 --> 05:34.112
oldest and the elder of the village. Where you 
would stop and say hello to a little kid and you'd

05:34.713 --> 05:40.079
give them candy, you've insulted the oldest 
person in that village. You've insulted the

05:40.099 --> 05:41.561
entire village. Also, touching the top of a 
child's head is very, the top of a child's head in

05:42.202 --> 05:51.793
our area was very, very sacred. And it was like a 
magnet. They said that if you touched the top of a

05:53.114 --> 05:55.337
child's head, it would suck the kindness out of 
their body into your body. And they believed it,

06:00.043 --> 06:03.366
and that's part of their beliefs or their customs. 
So first thing you do is grab a little kid's head and

06:03.386 --> 06:06.489
you shake the, hey, how you doing? You just, to 
those people, you've just taken all the kindness

06:07.089 --> 06:13.174
from that child, and you now own it. And you just 
insulted the family.

06:20.400 --> 06:21.721
Yeah. What is your very first memory of the country 
you were on? The smell. The country stunk. I landed

06:28.319 --> 06:39.432
in Da Nang, is where I first landed, and I was there 
in Da Nang about three days, but the first thing

06:28.319 --> 06:39.432
that I noticed, no, I wasn't there about three 
days, about two days I was in Da Nang. Getting off

06:41.113 --> 06:50.704
the plane, when I was on those little steps coming 
off, the smell, the stench, it smelled like the

06:41.113 --> 06:50.704
whole country was a cesspool. At that time, I did 
not know why, but then I thought everybody in the

06:51.528 --> 06:58.377
country, again, that was my ignorance of not 
knowing the people. Vietnam stunk because It's

07:02.463 --> 07:04.146
rice paddies. It's 90%, at least the areas I was in, 
it's mostly rice paddy and jungle. They use

07:08.553 --> 07:13.962
natural ingredients to fertilize their rice 
paddies. So everything stunk. The people had

07:16.927 --> 07:19.412
different ways of life. Again, the smell was the 
worst, I think. That's the first thing I remember.

07:23.178 --> 07:26.944
I still can smell the, at times, the stench of the 
country. Of course, they could have been burning

07:28.737 --> 07:30.541
Yeah, sure. I thought they could have been burning 
the shitters at that time, you know, the

07:30.902 --> 07:33.608
outhouses. And if they were, you know, the smell 
was going across the tarmac, which was our denang

07:34.189 --> 07:43.529
at that time. Did you at any time feel that South 
Vietnam was too corrupt or corrupt? South Vietnam

07:50.671 --> 07:52.373
could never win the war. We kind of knew that. What 
we wanted was to spend our tour and get out.

08:02.964 --> 08:10.212
The few men that I met, we had an interpreter, and 
over a year we became half-decent friends. He

08:11.133 --> 08:17.880
didn't trust me, and of course a lot of times I 
didn't quite trust him, but we became as best

08:11.133 --> 08:17.880
friends as we could.

08:19.835 --> 08:22.738
He had a brother that he paid to get out of war. 
There's a lot of people that could pay their way out

08:22.958 --> 08:25.281
of the army. Corruption was real, real big. So we 
knew that. And we just knew there's no way that

08:28.684 --> 08:32.208
that... There had to be a revolution to overthrow 
the corruption. So it was just no chance. And did

08:36.312 --> 08:44.140
you ever feel that the Arvin were ineffective 
or... Again, a problem... We had an Arvin. Again,

08:44.240 --> 08:46.102
one of our interpreters was an Arvin. And...

08:50.210 --> 08:54.757
He knew when we went out on patrol that, again, they 
had a different belief. Now, again, this is the

08:56.200 --> 08:57.882
area I was in. Before we get started, I've got to let 
you know, over the years I've found that talking to

08:57.922 --> 09:16.993
other people about Vietnam, what happens to me in 
Vietnam, you can talk to 50 other guys, and all 50

08:57.922 --> 09:16.993
have different interpretations, different 
ideas of Vietnam, even different terrain,

08:57.922 --> 09:16.993
everything, which is so different in areas. So I'm 
giving you what I saw and what I interpreted from

09:17.243 --> 09:21.589
this. The Arvin that I had in my unit,

09:21.609 --> 09:30.621
the first time we fought, you know, we had a small 
engagement. He wanted to run. I mean, he wanted to

09:32.704 --> 09:37.009
run the first thing, and he just knew the moment he 
got up, I would shoot him in the back. He knew that

09:37.290 --> 09:42.897
from the start, that any one of my units was going to 
kill him the moment that he got up to run. I thought

09:43.872 --> 09:44.813
he was a coward. I thought he was an absolute 
coward. And until one day, he's changed me a lot, my

09:47.796 --> 09:57.485
interpretation of Vietnam because he showed me 
their point of view, which was so different from

09:47.796 --> 09:57.485
mine. One day we were sitting there talking and I 
said, you know, I can't believe I'm in your country

09:58.166 --> 10:05.313
fighting for you and you're nothing but a bunch of 
cowards always running. And he got a little upset

10:06.955 --> 10:11.179
with me and he said, you are a a visitor in our 
country you're here to help us but you're so wrong

10:11.547 --> 10:35.479
and he he was very angry he told me he said you you 
marines up here uh brag about having the ten to one

10:11.547 --> 10:35.479
kill ratio in other words uh they'd say that our 
units up in the north had ten to one ratio would kill

10:11.547 --> 10:35.479
ten of the enemy before they finally kill us which 
is a very high high ratio and he said that means And I

10:35.898 --> 10:37.440
call it the John Wayne theory. The John Wayne 
theory is you fight to the end and you die a hero. He

10:41.765 --> 10:45.590
turned and he said, you know, that idea is totally 
stupid. He said, why do you do it that way? All you

10:48.333 --> 10:52.458
want to do is you shoot one today and you run. And you 
shoot one tomorrow and you run. And in one year, you

10:56.744 --> 11:01.770
have just killed 365 people. and I'm still alive, 
what is the ratio then? 365 to one compared to your

11:04.421 --> 11:07.090
10 to one. So they had a different idea about what is 
war. War to us was fight to the John Wayne, the

11:11.504 --> 11:15.557
Alamo, fight to the end. where they had an idea that 
you hit and you run. If you get into a situation

11:19.117 --> 11:22.380
where you think you're going to be surrounded, get 
out. But you're still allowed to fight another

11:22.901 --> 11:27.987
day, where we will sit there and keep fighting. So 
it's different ideas. I think their type of

11:29.849 --> 11:35.014
fighting could not, we could not work together. If 
that's what you mean by the arm, they could not

11:35.155 --> 11:39.339
fight with us because we had different theories. 
Guerrilla fighting or in the jungle fighting,

11:39.860 --> 11:42.202
perfect. But we did not fight that way, and that was 
the difference. Did you ever actually conduct a

11:45.406 --> 11:48.310
small unit action or any action? Oh, yeah, yeah, 
yeah. As I showed you earlier, going into Khe Sanh

11:50.913 --> 11:56.820
was the biggest joke. We thought we knew we died at 
Khe Sanh. It was a... And we walked right into it. A

12:04.409 --> 12:08.754
story out of Khe Sanh.

12:08.774 --> 12:10.877
1-9, there was nothing left of 1-9 or 2. 2-9 was just 
chopped up. There were areas they talked about,

12:14.583 --> 12:28.577
and I never saw this area, but they were talking 
about at night when you set up your concertina

12:14.583 --> 12:28.577
wire, you put cans of rocks in it, or you put a piece 
of metal into the concertina wire to where someone

12:14.583 --> 12:28.577
touches a rattle. You make noises, and you tell 
what the enemy is there touching the wire. Some of

12:32.221 --> 12:33.683
those nights, it got so dark. You couldn't see, and 
you kept asking for flares, but after a while, the

12:33.983 --> 12:40.810
enemy then sees you, so you can't put too many 
flares out. They said one of the sides during this

12:42.038 --> 12:47.565
time period, at night it got so dark they couldn't 
see. The next morning when the sun came up, they

12:47.585 --> 13:03.945
noticed that all the hands were taken off and 
little white crosses were placed in that

12:47.585 --> 13:03.945
position, saying that the enemy got into the 
concertina wire, made no noise, showed that they

12:47.585 --> 13:03.945
could have crossed into the wire any time they 
wanted to. Personally, I was too scared to believe

13:04.870 --> 13:06.873
something like that. I'm saying, God, if they 
could do that, then why are we still here? I mean,

13:09.957 --> 13:12.661
they were really pounding the hell out of us. It 
felt like you couldn't sleep at night. You tried

13:16.786 --> 13:17.587
the best. You would sleep for maybe, it felt like 30 
seconds because a shell was coming in almost that

13:17.607 --> 13:21.953
often. It was just constant pounding. But I guess 
we're, as Marines, we're just too stupid to give

13:24.477 --> 13:27.441
up. But one of the guys in a unit got his flight back. 
It's the day that you have to report to the name,

13:34.722 --> 13:38.968
you're going home. And he's in the middle of, right 
in the middle of Khe Sanh, surrounded by, we

13:39.369 --> 13:47.240
thought, the entire Asian population was around 
us, because hell, we were totally surrounded. We

13:48.702 --> 13:52.388
started laughing at him, that you ain't going 
home, mother, you're going to die right here. We

13:53.509 --> 13:54.831
laughed at him for about a day. It must have been the 
second day this idiot stood up, took his helmet

13:56.734 --> 14:01.641
off, We have what they call little Volkswagens. We 
call them a mule. They're like little

14:04.930 --> 14:06.994
Volkswagens. They took all the parts of them and 
made a flat bed across them. You had one place to

14:09.278 --> 14:12.203
steer it and carry things on it. He stood up on a mule 
and he just hollered out to the wire, people, I

14:12.223 --> 14:17.652
quit. I'm putting my rifle down. I'm putting my 
helmet down. I am not fighting anymore. I am going

14:22.280 --> 14:23.342
home. Okay? He gets in the mule. And he takes off, he 
puts some mail on the back behind this mule. He

14:34.503 --> 14:39.529
takes off to Dong Ha, which is right next to Quang 
Tri, going home. When he left, he snuck out. He just

14:42.472 --> 14:45.375
didn't just, you know, everybody watched him and 
waved at him, but he snuck out. We knew when he got

14:45.836 --> 14:49.179
out, you know, we'd never see that mother again. 
He's going to be just dead meat somewhere. About

14:52.465 --> 14:55.030
four hours later, he calls from Quang Tri. Nobody 
stopped him. He just saw no one the entire

14:56.734 --> 14:58.758
distance. Again, the Vietnamese believe that 
people that are crazy are sacred. Anybody crazy

15:06.333 --> 15:11.824
enough to go through three divisions of North 
Vietnamese regulars Got to be crazy. And he made it

15:14.028 --> 15:15.009
all the way back. You know, nuts like, things like 
that always happen. You know, you wonder. You

15:18.872 --> 15:21.335
know, everybody then started saying, people, I 
give up. You know, but it didn't work after they

15:21.395 --> 15:26.339
kept pounding the hell out of it. All right. What 
was the typical action you would describe that you

15:27.821 --> 15:33.366
were involved in as a, in those later periods as a 
patrol? Okay. I classify Vietnam as two wars. You

15:37.750 --> 15:41.153
have a good war and then you have a bad war. About, I 
would say, 66 through 69, it was a good war. Maybe

15:46.720 --> 15:48.563
even kind of 70, if you want to. It was to where the 
American public was not that much against it.

15:52.589 --> 15:54.432
People over there were still fighting the war.

15:57.517 --> 16:00.020
I was there during that time period. The bad war is 
the time period where People coming over were the

16:06.597 --> 16:18.017
protesters, the people that did not, of course, 
nobody wanted to be there, but these were the ones

16:06.597 --> 16:18.017
that were picketing and fighting against the war. 
So their patrols, I heard about, you know, smoking

16:19.400 --> 16:25.270
grass, going on patrol, most of the guys would die. 
I would be really afraid to have been over there

16:25.811 --> 16:29.618
during the 70s because of how... Sloppy, real 
sloppy, these people were. I always heard, you

16:35.370 --> 16:39.716
know, these guys that talk afterwards about being 
heroes. You know, there's no hero in Vietnam. All

16:41.418 --> 16:44.502
it was is a bunch of guys that try to stay alive. Some 
of them did some of the weirdest things by being

16:44.842 --> 16:47.525
heroes. But anyway, the Enormous Patrol for us was 
very easygoing. We worked together very well. the

16:57.053 --> 17:21.964
four guys that I was with some of my I call every so 
often but I've not seen him since we left since I've

16:57.053 --> 17:21.964
left Vietnam or they left also of course I didn't 
ask you I didn't answer your question too well

16:57.053 --> 17:21.964
other typical action what was it like you mean 
going on patrol yeah most of the times we had a

16:57.053 --> 17:21.964
three-day patrol four-day patrol you're really 
going for us a lot of times we were just out seeing

17:23.733 --> 17:52.626
what's out there and if you're talking about 
different types we had a patrol you'd go out past

17:23.733 --> 17:52.626
the wire for a few days just checking to see what's 
or even one day you're going out just see what's out

17:23.733 --> 17:52.626
there and coming back you had other ones where we 
would have to go to vanden grift or to any place like

17:23.733 --> 17:52.626
that where you just take off and put it all the way 
there

17:23.733 --> 17:52.626
gosh i wish i could in the jungle was uh The most 
frightening of them all to me. The jungle was scary

17:56.425 --> 17:59.289
because you couldn't see ahead of them. It was so 
hot. There's no sun. The humidity just drained the

18:01.212 --> 18:03.976
energy out of you. The heat was just terrible. But 
you couldn't see. That was a big thing. You were

18:08.483 --> 18:09.304
walking along. You had to be so quiet because you 
make any noise, those people can almost walk 20

18:09.324 --> 18:16.594
feet away from you, and you will never even see 
them. You'll only hear or smell them. Same way for

18:18.457 --> 18:19.398
our direction. Typical action. Let's see if I can 
give one. We took three days, or two days of

18:23.504 --> 18:27.269
C-rations, or three days, we were out for three 
days. We used C-rations or K-rations, which

18:27.709 --> 18:34.698
tasted like, you know, 20-year-old vomit. And we 
couldn't heat it up. We had to eat it cold, which

18:37.100 --> 18:39.103
made it even taste worse. But you were so hot and so 
drained of fluid, you really didn't want to eat

18:39.824 --> 18:45.150
anything. All you wanted to do was take down the 
liquids. God, I... I wish I could help you more on

18:52.495 --> 18:55.679
it, but that's just when we'd go out on patrols. We 
were scared. Of course, there are fun times. I

18:59.845 --> 19:01.347
mean, there's a weird time, too. Now, that's what I 
like to remember, the weird times. You'll get out,

19:05.252 --> 19:08.837
and you'll have these monkeys. We call them rock 
apes. They'll throw rocks at you. You're sitting

19:12.362 --> 19:14.505
down there on the ground, not bothering anybody. 
Also, you have these things thrown at you from, we

19:14.885 --> 19:18.330
call them rock apes. They'll throw anything they 
can get their hands on. to get you out of their area.

19:22.487 --> 19:23.668
They thought that was their area. And idiots like 
us, instead of shooting them, we throw rocks back

19:24.469 --> 19:27.773
at them. And then you have a firefight between 
monkeys and marines over their little area. There

19:34.160 --> 19:36.222
was a time where we went after a bingo tiger. I 
showed you the picture, didn't I? I didn't shoot

19:39.966 --> 19:40.767
it. Some guy shot a... We went out on patrol to kill a 
bingo tiger. There was like an operation of

19:46.393 --> 19:48.135
maybe... Four or five hundred went out on a hunt of 
this rabid bingo tiger. It was told whoever got it

19:53.499 --> 19:56.204
could keep it. It was their skin. They could take 
the skin home. A Marine shot it with an M16, one shot

20:01.934 --> 20:06.562
by total accident. The guy said he was just 
shooting in the area and the tiger ran into the

20:06.582 --> 20:09.988
bullet. But he hit him right in the head, just blew 
the top of his head off. Well, they drug it back,

20:13.572 --> 20:21.381
they hooked it up in the camp, they hooked it on a 
telephone pole, and let's sit there like an honor,

20:13.572 --> 20:21.381
like this is what we got. Found out the next day it's 
rabbits. So the colonel of our company found out

20:27.088 --> 20:33.295
that we have to burn it. What you have to do to a 
rabbit animal out there is you dig a hole, you bury

20:33.335 --> 20:38.541
it, You dig a hole first, then you cover it with 
gasoline, you burn it, pour lye on it, then you bury

20:38.977 --> 20:45.986
it, and you don't get away from that area for a 
while. That's what they did. But our colonel

20:48.309 --> 20:49.130
didn't. 101 Airborne just moved up right next to 
us. We never saw stakes. We never had T-bone

20:55.359 --> 20:56.680
stakes. They did. Their colonel said, God, I wish I 
had that skin because, man, that's a beautiful

20:59.444 --> 21:06.854
thing to take home, to lay on the ground, to say 
that, you know, he'd probably go home and say he

20:59.444 --> 21:06.854
shot it himself, you know. Who in the hell would 
know? So our colonel, knowing it's rabbit, said,

21:08.558 --> 21:16.268
I'll tell you what, the guy, the boy doesn't want 
the skin at all, or the animal. He gave it to me. I'll

21:17.770 --> 21:25.379
tell you what, if you give me one of your bins full of 
steaks to feed my guys, we'll give you the skin. The

21:25.399 --> 21:27.181
guy said, hey, great, we'll do that. So he takes the 
steaks that he was going to give to his own

21:27.442 --> 21:37.975
servicemen, the Army, which hell, they get them 
all the time, gave them to us. He has, we call them

21:39.203 --> 21:43.710
like ditzy dumpsters, or big metal containers of 
refrigeration. Well, he only had one

21:44.071 --> 21:51.202
refrigerator left with the steaks that the guys 
were going to eat for the rest of the month, which is

21:44.071 --> 21:51.202
mostly ground meat and stuff like this. So he 
throws that carcass into that, their other

21:51.903 --> 22:01.077
refrigerator, waiting until someone processes 
the skin, okay? So he called over his doctors. We

22:03.226 --> 22:05.709
already had this big, ditzy dumpster with steaks. 
